      "name": "Edit",
      "args": {
        "replace_all": false,
        "file_path": "/home/anup/claude-projects/stm32-substrate/tests/fixtures/projects/F-PROJ-NUCLEO-L476RG/stm32-project.jsonc",
        "old_string": "  \"firmware\": {\n    \"flash_address\": \"0x08000000\",\n    \"device_family\": \"STM32L4\",\n    \"board\": \"NUCLEO-L476RG\"\n  },",
        "new_string": "  \"firmware\": {\n    \"flash_address\": \"0x08000000\",\n    \"device_family\": \"STM32L4\",\n    \"board\": \"NUCLEO-L476RG\",\n    // VCP-004 2026-06-12: device USART2 measured via SWD register read \u2014\n    // BRR=174 @ 80 MHz PCLK1 => 459,770 baud (= standard 460800, 0.22% err), 8N1.\n    \"uart_baud\": 460800\n  },"
      }
    },
    {
      "name": "Bash",
      "args": {
        "command": "stm32 vcp reconnect --max-wait 5 && stm32 vcp send \"hi\" --timeout 4",
        "description": "Reconnect VCP at new baud and verify with probe line"
      }
    }
  ],
  "final_text": "I'll diagnose this as a VCP-004 flow: confirm the garbage, read the device's actual UART config from its registers via the debug surface, compute the real baud, then reconnect the VCP to match.\n\nFirst, let me see what's on the bench and capture a sample of the garbage:\nN6 port is silent (zero bytes in 4 s). Now the L476 port:\nZero bytes even raw \u2014 the soft reset may have left the core halted under SWD. Let me try a hard (NRST) reset and listen with the substrate's reader (which asserts DTR, unlike `cat`):\nNo `vcp` section \u2014 the VCP falls back to the default 115200, hence the mismatch. Let me check the schema for the exact key shape:\nBaud must live in the runtime-defaults config:\nNo baud key in either schema \u2014 let me check the VCP API spec for how baud is resolved:\nFound it: `firmware.uart_baud` is the descriptor field (fallback 115200 \u2014 exactly the mismatch). Fixing the descriptor to match the device's actual config:\nFixed and verified \u2014 clean echo at the new baud (`sent \"hi\"` \u2192 `reply \"hi\"`, no garbage).\n\n## What was wrong\n\nThe NUCLEO-L476RG's USART2 (the ST-LINK VCP UART) is running at **460800 baud**, but the terminal was reading at the 115200 fallback. Ground truth from SWD register reads (VCP-004 flow):\n\n| Evidence | Value | Meaning |\n|---|---|---|\n| `USART2.CR1` = 0x0D | M1=0, M0=0, PCE=0, OVER8=0 | 8 data bits, no parity, \u00d716 oversampling |\n| `USART2.CR2.STOP` = 0 | | 1 stop bit |\n| `USART2.BRR` = **174** | | baud = kernel clock \u00f7 174 |\n| `RCC`: MSI 4 MHz \u2192 PLL (N=40, R=\u00f72) \u2192 SYSCLK 80 MHz, PPRE1=\u00f71, CCIPR USART2SEL=PCLK1 | | kernel clock = **80 MHz** |\n| **Computed** | 80 MHz \u00f7 174 = 459,770 | = standard **460800** (0.22% error) \u2192 **460800 8N1** |\n\n## The fix\n\n- Added `firmware.uart_baud: 460800` to `tests/fixtures/projects/F-PROJ-NUCLEO-L476RG/stm32-project.jsonc` (with a comment citing the register evidence) \u2014 previously the descriptor had no `uart_baud`, so the VCP fell back to 115200.\n- `stm32 vcp reconnect` re-attached `/dev/ttyACM1` at 460800; a probe `send` round-tripped cleanly.\n\nTwo notes:\n\n1. **If you're also using an external terminal** (minicom/picocom), set it to **460800 8N1** \u2014 and run `stm32 vcp close` first so it can take the port.\n2. The descriptor edit is uncommitted. Also worth knowing: this firmware appears to be the echo-style console (it only transmits in response to input after reset), so a silent `tail` is normal \u2014 `send` is the right liveness probe here."
}